		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Ethic of reciprocity</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-move" style="">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width: 52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mergefrom.svg" class="image" title="Mergefrom.svg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Mergefrom.svg/50px-Mergefrom.svg.png" width="50" height="20" border="0" /></a></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="">It has been suggested that <i><a href="/wiki/Norm_of_reciprocity" title="Norm of reciprocity">Norm of reciprocity</a></i> be <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Merging_and_moving_pages" title="Wikipedia:Merging and moving pages" class="mw-redirect">merged</a> into this article or section. (<a href="/wiki/Talk:Ethic_of_reciprocity" title="Talk:Ethic of reciprocity">Discuss</a>)</td>
</tr>
</table>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_022.jpg" class="image" title="The Parable of the Good Samaritan"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_022.jpg/180px-Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_022.jpg" width="180" height="222" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Vincent_Willem_van_Gogh_022.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The <a href="/wiki/Parable_of_the_Good_Samaritan" title="Parable of the Good Samaritan">Parable of the Good Samaritan</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>ethic of reciprocity</b> (also known as the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Rule" title="Golden Rule">Golden Rule</a>) is an ethical code that states one has a right to just treatment, and a responsibility to ensure justice for others. Reciprocity is arguably the most essential basis for the modern concept of <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">human rights</a>, though it has its critics.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A key element of the golden rule is that a person attempting to live by this rule treats all people, not just members of his or her <a href="/wiki/In-group" title="In-group" class="mw-redirect">in-group</a>, with consideration. The golden rule has its roots in a wide range of world cultures, and is a standard which different cultures use to resolve conflicts.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Principal philosophers and religious figures have stated it in different ways.</p>
<p>Today the most common English phrasing of the Golden Rule is "Do unto others as you would have them do unto you." The "Do unto others" part first appeared in English in a Catholic Catechism probably in 1567, but certainly in the reprint of 1583<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
